# Fluff Date: 2026-03-02 15:52:16
<overview>
<p>The Bailey Armored Car represents Gienah Automotive's direct response to the demonstrated inadequacy of standard civilian security vehicles against Battle Armor-equipped adversaries. Developed after the 3059 Briggs robbery incident on Alexandria exposed the vulnerability of existing armored cars to modern military threats, the Bailey incorporates recovered First Star League technology into a wheeled platform substantially more capable than the Knox-type vehicles it was designed to supplement. Weighing more than twice as much as the Knox and costing six times as much, the Bailey is explicitly positioned as a premium security transport for clients whose cargo and personnel justify serious investment in protection. Gienah Automotive, headquartered on Gienah in the Lyran Alliance, has received consistent orders from mercenary security contractors, planetary governments, and commercial enterprises since the Bailey entered production, establishing the vehicle as the premier civilian armored car of its generation.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Bailey is built around a wheeled medium platform powered by a fusion engine, providing substantially faster speeds than comparable internal combustion designs while eliminating fuel range constraints. Its armor suite provides fifty-eight points of BAR 10 protection, a dramatic improvement over the Knox-class baseline that offers meaningful resistance against light military weapons and reliable protection from Battle Armor-class threats. The armored chassis modification reinforces the vehicle's structural integrity beyond standard civilian construction standards.</p><p>The Bailey's armament centers on two turret-mounted small pulse lasers supplemented by a turret-mounted anti-missile system with twelve rounds of AMS ammunition. The pulse lasers provide accurate, heat-efficient firepower against lightly armored targets, while the AMS offers active defense against guided munitions, a critical capability in threat environments where shoulder-launched missiles are readily available to criminal or insurgent forces. Advanced fire control supports both weapon systems, providing targeting capability well above the basic fire control found in Knox-type vehicles. The Bailey carries three tons of standard cargo, sufficient for a small dismounted security team alongside high-value cargo, giving it a viable secondary role as a light armored personnel carrier. The wheeled drive system performs well on paved and improved surfaces but restricts the Bailey to urban and developed terrain, requiring combined arms support for operations beyond established road networks.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>Bailey Armored Cars serve primarily in urban and developed-terrain security roles throughout the Lyran Alliance and in smaller numbers across the broader Inner Sphere via mercenary and commercial export channels. Their most common operators are planetary governments, banking institutions, and mercenary security contractors requiring vehicles capable of resisting Battle Armor-class threats. The anti-missile system makes the Bailey particularly valuable in environments where guided munitions are a credible threat from criminal or insurgent forces. The three-ton cargo bay allows operators to transport a small security team alongside high-value cargo, supporting combined escort and transport missions with a single vehicle. The Bailey's lack of off-road capability restricts it to urban environments and paved infrastructure, and operators in rural or undeveloped areas typically pair it with tracked or hover alternatives capable of operating in rough terrain.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Bailey Armored Car emerged directly from the 3059 Briggs robbery incident on Alexandria, in which a criminal organization using Battle Armor overpowered a Knox convoy despite its BattleMech escort. The scale and audacity of the robbery demonstrated that even well-planned commercial security operations could not protect high-value cargo against adversaries with access to modern military hardware. The incident received significant attention across Lyran Alliance commercial channels, generating industry demand for a security transport capable of engaging Battle Armor-class threats directly rather than relying on BattleMech escorts that could not always be economically justified.</p><p>Gienah Automotive responded by designing a purpose-built upgrade around recovered First Star League military equipment, sourcing fusion engine components, pulse laser systems, and anti-missile hardware through channels opened by the renewed interest in rediscovered Star League technology during the late Clan Invasion period. The resulting design entered production on Gienah shortly after 3062, drawing on the company's established wheeled vehicle manufacturing infrastructure and leveraging the supply chains Gienah Automotive had built over prior decades of civilian transport production.</p><p>The Bailey commanded strong initial orders despite its significant price premium. Mercenary units seeking contract work in security transportation roles found the Bailey's capabilities particularly attractive, as the anti-missile system and pulse lasers allowed a single vehicle to provide credible deterrence against the armed criminal organizations and light insurgent forces that dominated security contracting work during the Civil War era. Planetary governments with active criminal threats or low-level insurgencies adopted the Bailey as a cost-effective alternative to deploying dedicated military vehicles for constabulary duties. Gienah Automotive's production line maintained consistent output through the Civil War period and into the Jihad era, with the Lyran Alliance and later the Commonwealth Worlds of Europe remaining the primary customer base through the Dark Age period and into the ilClan era.</p>
</history>

